#Text=Robert Bennet ( bishop )
#Text=Robert Bennet ( Bennett ) ( died 1617 ) was an English Anglican bishop and the Dean of Windsor .
#Text=Bennet was born in Baldock , Hertfordshire to Leonard Bennet and his wife , Margaret Langley .
#Text=He matriculated at Trinity College , Cambridge in 1563 , graduating B.A. in 1567 , and becoming a minor Fellow in the same year . [ 1 ] [ 2 ]
#Text=He became a full Fellow in 1570 , in which year he also gained his M. A , .
#Text=He was incorporated at Oxford in 1572 , at which time he opposed John Whitgift 's redrafted Cambridge University statutes , and in 1576 he served as university preacher at Cambridge .
#Text=As a young man he was noted for his good looks and as a royal tennis player .

#Text=After obtaining his B. Th . in 1577 , he was referred to as Erudito Benedicte because , in the words of John Harington , " ' he would tosse an Argument in the Schools , better than a Ball in the Tennis-court " . [ 3 ] [ 4 ]
#Text=In 1583 , Bennet became master of the Hospital of St Cross in Winchester and left Cambridge .
#Text=Together with Thomas Bilson , the warden of Winchester College , he became active in attempts to end Catholic recusancy .

#Text=This work brought him to the attention of William Cecil , Lord Burghley , who appointed Bennet as one of his personal chaplains and , in March 1596 , aided his appointment as Dean of Windsor in succession to William Day .
#Text=He combined his work as dean with that as master of St Cross . [ 3 ]
#Text=He offended Elizabeth I by preaching against her proposed marriage to François , Duke of Anjou . [ 2 ]
#Text=Despite Bennet 's opposition to royal demands that he cede property under his control , he was elected as Bishop of Hereford in January 1603 .
#Text=He had turned down the offer of the bishopric of Salisbury in 1598 because that had required him to alienate some of his property rights .

#Text=He determined in his new role to continue his suppression of Catholic recusancy but was unsuccessful in persuading his superiors – such as James I – to grant the diocesan commission that he envisaged to be his instrument in achieving this end .
#Text=His health began to fail , which he blamed on the " cold and rheumatic " climate of the diocese .

#Text=He failed in his attempt to move to the vacant bishopric at Worcester in 1610 and subsequently used his position to promote evangelical work and to improve the education of clergymen , [ 3 ] notably through the Leintwardin lecture . [ 5 ]
#Text=Bennet was married but details of his wife are unknown .
#Text=He left a substantial sum of money for his burial expenses and detailed instructions regarding what should be done at his death , which occurred in October 1617 .
#Text=[ lower-alpha 1 ]
#Text=He had designed his own white alabaster effigy , which still exists in Hereford cathedral , where he was buried close to where his wife sat .
#Text=His heir was a nephew , also called Robert Bennet , [ 3 ]
#Text=and his successor at Hereford was Francis Godwin , the author of numerous books including the remarkable piece of science fiction titled The Man in the Moone . [ 8 ]
#Text=He left money to the cathedral , Trinity College in Cambridge , Oxford University and the poor of various places , including that of his birth , Baldock , [ 7 ]
